merged_product_data.model: Collectors choice CC28 Ronnie Montrose Les Paul
merged_product_data.description:
Gibson Collectors Choice The following instrument was built to honour one of American Rocks most famous guitarists, Ronnie Montrose. The instrument is replicated from his original 1958 Les Paul Standard which saw action throughout his illustrious career Gibson Collectors Choice Ronnie Montrose Les Paul

General

  • Model:Collector's Choice No #28 Ronnie Montrose
  • Color:'STP 'Burst'
  • Finish:Nitrocelluloid
  • Strings:010 - 046 Gibson
  • Limited to 300 piece worldwide (availability of apropriate woods)
Top
  • Material:Genuine 1-Pc. Mahogany, hand-selected, lightweight
  • Top:2-Pc. Figured Maple
  • Binding:Creme

Neck

  • Material:1-Pc. Genuine Mahogany
  • Profile:Ronnie Montrose 58
  • Fingerboard:1-Pc. Indian Rosewood
  • Fingerboard Radius:12'
  • Frets:22 Reissue
  • Binding:Creme
  • Inlays:Aged Nitrocelluloid Trapezoid
  • Nut Material:Bone (original Nylon-Nut included)
  • Width at Nut:1.687' / 42,8 mm
  • Scale length:24 3/4' / 628 mm

Electric

  • Neck Pickup:CustomBucker, 8,00 kOhm, Cover True Historic Replica Aged Nickel
  • Bridge Pickup:CustomBucker, 7,40 kOhm, Cover True Historic Replica Aged Nickel
  • Potentiometer:2x Volume (500 kOhm, 2x Tone (500 kOhm )
  • Capacitors:Bumble Bee
  • Switch:3-Way Toggle

Hardware

  • Bridge:Aged ABR with Thumbwheels
  • Tailpiece:Aged Reissue Lightweight Aluminum
  • Tuning Keys:Reissue Kluson Deluxe , Single Band, 12:1

Accessories

  • Custom Shop Les Paul Reissue Hardshell Case, Aged / Lacquered Reissue Brown w. Pink Fur Lining
  • Collector's Choice Certificate of Authenticity
  • Gibson Warranty-Card

merged_product_data.model: L122 Organ owned & used by Rick Wakeman of YES
merged_product_data.description:
We are happy to offer the following items from the personal private collection of iconic keyboardist and synth collector Rick Wakeman. Rick career has spanned over 50 years including his time with The Strawbs and YES through to his session work with David Bowie, Black Sabbath and countless others. Alongside this, Rick's own solo career has pushed the boundaries of possibilities in terms of his use of the synthesiser including his albums Journey to the Centre of the Earth and the Six wives of Henry VIII. Rick is now pleased to be offering his fans the chance to owns some of the pieces which have sculpted his sound across his extensive career. Please find details of these pieces as below:

HAMMOND L122 ORGAN

Tone Wheel Organ

Double Manual Purchased from Chingford Organ Studios

Verification

Each item will come with written verification direct from Rick Wakeman to confirm his ownership and use of the items. Pricing All items have been in storage many since the 1970s and will require servicing by the purchaser. This costing is reflected in the pricing of each item.

merged_product_data.description:
JEFF LYNNE IDLE RACE AC30

The following amplifier was one of Jeff Lynne’s first guitar amplifiers, purchased in circa 1964 was used in many of Jeff Lynne's early musical collaborations, details as follows:

Vox Ac30

1964 ( Circa )

Grey Panel

2+12 Speakers

Hand painted to rear “ The Idle Race “

Condition - Used

The Idle Race History

The Idle Race were a British rock group from Birmingham who in the late 1960s and early 1970s had a cult following and in addition to being the springboard for Jeff Lynne, the band holds a place of significance in British Midlands' pop-rock history as a link between the Move, Electric Light Orchestra, the Steve Gibbons Band and Mike Sheridan & The Nightriders.

Link - The Idle Race

Jeff Lynne's First Amplifier

Please see abstract taken from Beatles “ Fab Four Blog “ that discusses Jeff's First Ever Guitar Amplifier

'However The Andicaps didn't last and in 1964 Jeff decided to join another local band called The Chads. it was also in that year that Lynne bought his first electric guitar, a second hand Burns Sonic along with a Vox AC30 amp.'

Comments

The above will be of interest to those players and collectors whom have interest in an amplifier that was at the beginning of the career of one of Britain’s most highly acclaimed musicians, producers and songwriters that being Jeff Lynne.

THE MAGIC NUMBER The following instrument carries the same year and month of production as George Harrison's famed and fabled missing 360 12, which he used on many classic Beatles performances, including The Beatles last ever paid public concert at Candlestick Park San Francisco on 29th of August 1966. Details as follows: Rickenbacker 360 12 1965 (July) Serial EG Fireglo Internally / Externally Original Condition 8.5/10 (Normal, Light Playing Wear) Original SilverCase Rarity The above instrument was produced by the Rickenbacker Guitar Company in July of 1965 which was only 3-4 weeks prior to the presentation of a Rickenbacker 360 to George Harrison in Minneapolis in August 1965 so may be one of the magic 5 instruments that would have been shipped by Rickenbacker prior to the presentation in August 1965 History Of Presentation At the end of this press conference on 21st August 1965, George Harrison is surprised as he was presented a Rickenbacker 360 electric 12-string guitar by B-Sharp Music, a local area guitar shop at the time. It was the second of this particular model of guitar that George was able to add to his collection. Harrison would play his new Rickenbacker on stage that evening. As George received the guitar, John Lennon smiled and joked: 'That's fab, that! Where's mine?” Comments The above instrument is a rare and highly desired Rickenbacker model that carries the same detailed specification as one of the most famous and fabled of all missing Beatle instruments, that being George Harrison's 1965 360 12.

THE BEST OF BRITISH TONE

The following is one of the rarest and most desired of all Marshall amplifiers, featuring the rare Gold Block Logo, smooth pebble Levant, and early RS Transformers.

HISTORY

The amplifier was purchased from its second owner, who was gifted it by the original owner in 1970 and has remained in the same ownership.

Marshall JTM45

1965

Gold Block Logo

Smooth Black Tolex

Gold Plexi Front

White Rear

Silver Disc Controls

RS Mains & Output Transformers

Internally/Externally Original (All components original, untouched)

Condition 8.75/10 (Light, normal wear)

HISTORY OF PRODUCTION

The first series Gold Block Logo JTM45s were produced in exceptionally small numbers and are highly sought after by both players and collectors due to their rarity and exceptional tonal qualities.

SOUND/TONE

Due to their high-grade component quality, values, and circuit design, these early Marshall 45s have tonal characteristics similar to a Fender Tweed amplifier but with more gain/drive, synonymous with classic Marshall British tone. In collector/player terms, this is the ultimate JTM45.

Comments

One of the world’s most desired vintage amplifiers, both in tone and rarity. Favored by many iconic British artists, including Eric Clapton and Pete Townshend.

THE GARY MOORE TELECASTER

We are happy to offer the following instrument that has direct links and association to two of the most respected and influential of all guitarists that being George Harrison of the Beatles and blues rock guitarist, the great Gary Moore. Details as follows:

THE FRITZ BROTHERS HARRISON- MOORE TELECASTER

Telecaster Custom

US Boutique/Luthier Produced

Sunburst Finish

Bound Body

3 EMGs

Rosewood Neck

White Pearl Guard (Comes with spare/added Harrison Specification Tortoise shell Guard)

Condition Used/Played

Original Road / Touring Case

FRITZ BROTHERS HISTORY

The Fritz brothers are a US based luthier built guitar company which has produced guitars for many respected and iconic artists that include Aerosmith, Roy Buchanan, Keith Richards, Darryl Jones, Randy Jackson, Bill Bottrell and the Bangles

GARY MOORE - GEORGE HARRISON CONNECTION

In the early 1990's George Harrison and Gary Moore lived in Henley on Thames, London and based on there musical connection with other local famed musicians, met on numerous occasions at George's home for rehearsal and recording purposes. On one such meeting George Harrison, at the request off Gary, loaned him his personal sunburst Fritz Brothers Telecaster to record a track on Moore's 1989 album, After the War. On it's return, Moore requested the Fritz Brothers build him a guitar that carried the exact same specification as the instrument favoured by George.

Provenance

This instrument was sold as part of Gary’s Moore's extensive collection in 2016 by Bonhams auction house and comes with provenance from the auction sale as well as being featured along with George Harrison's on the Fritz Bros Company web Site

Comments

The above instrument was personally owned and used by one of the worlds most respected blues rock guitarist , Gary Moore whom based on his close relationship with George, built an instrument that carried the same specification as his friends most favoured Telecaster and gary used the instrument for both live , touring and recording purposes until it was sold at the Bonhams 2016 Moore Sale

Alongside this, Rick's own solo career has pushed the boundaries of possibilities in terms of his use of the synthesiser including his albums Journey to the Centre of the Earth and the Six wives of Henry VIII. This is a detailed replica of the original 1965 Burns Buzzaround pedal that to many is the HOLY GRAIL OF EFFECTS.

The Buzzaround also came in a unique wedge shaped casing with controls on the front. This added to the pedals uniqueness. and was most famously used by Robert Fripp.

merged_product_data.description:
THE BIRTH OF THE CLASH

We are happy to offer the following instrument from one of the most respected guitarists of the Post Punk Movement that being the late Keith Levene, founding member of the Clash. Hailed as an innovative guitarist who helped shape the sound of punk, Levene cowrote the song “What’s My Name” from The Clash’s 1977 debut album. Please see details as follows

History

Please see link for full history and credits of Artist

Joe Strummer, Mick Jones, Terry Chimes, Paul Simenon and Keith Levine became The Clash in late 1976. Inspired by seeing The Sex Pistols and the music they were making, the boys quickly evolved a stance and image that endeared them to the punk masses. Their first outing was a gig at their rehearsal studios in Camden for journalists and friends which caused Giovanni Dadomo a reviewer for Sounds to opine 'I think they're the first band to come along who'll really frighten the Sex Pistols shitless.' Indeed their first public gig was supporting The Sex Pistols at The Screen On The Green Islington London. Charles Shaar Murray, in a famous quote he wishes he'd never made, said in the NME they '..are the kind of garage band who should speedily be returned to their garage, preferably with the motor running.' This was too much for Levine who left leaving the boys as a four piece.

Fernandes E series

1990s

Grey Burst

Flamed top

Humbucker

Hot Rail in Neck

Fernandez Floyd Rose Style Tremolo

Condition - Stage , Tour Used

Signed verification confirming ownership and use by the artist

The Levene Style

According to John Frusciante of the Red Hot Chili Peppers, Levene's style was “spectacular , .explored the possibilities of what you can do with the guitar'.Upon his death, Massive Attack described Levene as an 'artist, architect and re-inventor of punk rock”.

Comments

The above instrument will be to those players , collectors and investors whom have interest in an instrument that was personally owned and used by this highly respected Post Punk Guitarist and founding member of both the Clash and PiL.

We are pleased to offer the following classic boutique amplifier

The 45W Roseland is a purist design, all tube 1×12 combo with reverb and tremolo powered by a pair of 6L6 tubes. Its’ single channel Multi Voice preamp offers an incredibly wide range of voicings ranging from sparkly cleans to thick, woody tweed to driven plexi crunch and grind. It includes tube driven spring reverb with both mix and dwell controls to fine tune the reverb sound to be as splashy or subtle as you choose. Its bias modulation tremolo has a particularly smooth and round effect. The solid wood cabinet with unified baffle/body construction delivers a lively, deeply resonant, and unconstricted sound. A unique master volume circuit is extremely transparent, maintaining the same sound and vivid presence all the way down to bedroom volume.

THE ULTIMATE TONAL PACKAGE We are pleased to offer the following package of boutique pedals for this who require and appreciate the unique tonal differences betweens the effects which defined the history of rock and roll. The Connoisseur of Fuzz collection comprises of 6 unique effects detailing the history of British Fuzz Box Development. The package included the following effects

  • MKI Tone Bender
  • MKI.5 Tone Bender
  • Professional MKII Tone Bender
  • Zonk Machine
  • Buzzaround
  • PepBox

MKI Tone Bender Spec: The BPC MKI Tone Bender is a detailed replica of the original 1965 Metal Case Tone Bender pedal created by Gary Hurst in London, England. The BPC MKI features the same transistor specification as the original so includes 1x OC75 + 2x 2G381 this configuaration has a unique tone which cannot be replicated by the often offered 3xOC75 version. It was this version which found its way into the hands of artists such as Jeff Beck, Pete Townsend and Mick Ronson and can be heard on many classic tracks such as ‘Hang onto yourself’ and ‘Moonage Daydream’. MKI.5 Tone Bender Spec: Often known as the mythical fuzz due to the very few original examples which exist, the MKI.5 Tone Bender was produced in 1966 and was the first tone bender that featured the iconic Grey Hammerite Aluminium Casing. The MKI.5 featured a different circuit than the earlier production MK I and consisted of a 2x OC75 transistor circuit At the time of production one of these rare fuzzes managed to find its way into Abbey Road Studios and was pictured being used by George Harrison of The Beatles. Professional MKII Tone Bender Spec: The BPC MKII Tone Bender OC81D is a detailed replica of the 1966 PROFESSIONAL MK II Tone Bender pedals created by Gary Hurst. The circuit unlike the MK 1.5 had a 3 Transistor circuit which, based on production/supply comprised of either OC75’s or OC81D transistors. This OC81D Loaded MK II can be heard on many Jimmy/Led Zeppelin Tracks such as ‘Whole lotta love’. This was the pedal seen being used by Jimmy on the recent ‘It Might get loud ‘ documentary. BuzzaroundSpec:

This is a detailed replica of the original 1965 Burns Buzzaround pedal that to many is the HOLY GRAIL OF EFFECTS.The Buzzaround is a unique fuzz which utilised 3 x NKT213 transistors and for the first time offered a timbre control which gives different dimension to your fuzz tone. The Buzzaround also came in a unique wedge shaped casing with controls on the front. This added to the pedals uniqueness. and was most famously used by Robert Fripp.

BPC Pepbox Spec: BPC PEPBOX is a detailed replica of the original unit designed by Pepe Rush for WEM around 1965. This pedal was most famously used by John Lennon at Abbey Road studios during the Revolver Session and can be seen on many photographs from the period. The pedal features 2 Germanium ACY41 Transistors as per the original unit and is housed in a metal enclosure with engraved logo and control panels. The front panel features effect which acts as the gain and then a Level control for the overall volume. Notes:This is theultimate package for any fuzz freak or recording musician, adding the true sounds of the 60s to your recordingrepertoire. With our Black Friday deal this is available for a limited period with 40% off RRP WHILE STOCKS LAST!

We are happy to offer the following items from the personal private collection of iconic keyboardist and synth collector Rick Wakeman. THE DUMBLE EXPORT MODEL The following amplifier was produced in conjunction the worlds most iconic of all Amplifier Builders that is the Late Howard Alexander Dumble and his German Distributor that Being Applied Acoustics whom marketed under there own Brand Name Kitty Hawk Dumble Story / Applied Acoustics History In the late 1970s , two German brothers , Wolfram and Gondola Roam had a company called Applied Acoustics in Bochum West Germany , Applied acoustics was the authorised imported / distributor for mesa Boogie and Dumble Amplifiers for the European Market .In the early 1980s , the high US $$$ rate and even higher shipping costs created very expensive prices for both Mesa Boogie and Dumble Amplifiers Distributed in Europe . Applied acoustics made an agrement with Howard Dumble that he would Ship amplifiers without a cabinet ,speaker and transformers to save on shipping costs and the cabinets would be produced in Germany Also if customers wanted to add reverb or effects loop applied acoustics were authorised by Dumble to make these adjustments Therefore Howard dumble passed a lot of technical and build information regards to his amplifiers to his European partners Applied Acoustics , Dumble hand built the amplifiers himself and based on the six to ninth month lead time applied acoustics decided to build there own amplifiers under the Kitty Hawk Brand that would be an exact replica of the Silver Face Dumble Overdrive amplifiers that they were selling , these first 20 Kitty Hawk Prototype Models featured original Dumble Components , Boards , Spares that had Been Supplied by Howard Dumble for both service and production reasons , when Howard Dumble was aware of the Kitty Hawk Production he halted distribution with Applied acoustics and then started to Gunk His Circuit to hide his secrets , component layouts , the rest as they say is history Components / Boards The following amplifier was one of 20 Original Kitty Hawk Branded amplifiers that featured various original Howard Dumble Supplied Circuit Boards , Components that were assembled by Applied Acoustics in Germany and marketed under the New Kitty Hawk Brand Specification - As follows Dumble / Kitty Hawk Overdrive Amplifier 1979 / 80 50 Watts Serial 006 Original Howard Dumble Components / Boards ( Original Solder / Untouched ) Mahogany Cabinet Whicker Grill Internally / Eternally Original Dumble / Kitty Hawk Speaker Cabinet 2+12 Vertical Original Altec Speakers ( Not Fitted although included ) Open Back Mahogany Cabinet Whicker Grill Internally / Externally Original Sound / Tone The amplifier has that Classic Dumble Tone , clean although with an underlying overdriven tone that has bene favoured by many of the worlds most respected and iconic of all guitarists from SRV , ERIC CLAPTON , LARRY CARLTON , ROBBIN FORD , JOE BONAMASSA Etc The Market The interest and demand for an original Howard Dumble amplifiers is exceptionally high with current prices in excess of £150,000 ( $180,000) so do feel the pricing of the above being exceptionally realistic for those whom require the sound , tone and direct association with this Legendary and Iconic Builder Dumble

merged_product_data.description:
Leslie West first gained recognition as the lead guitarist for the Vagrants, a locally popular 1960s Long Island group. One of that band's singles was produced by Felix Pappalardi, a bass player who also produced Cream. After the Vagrants and Cream split up, Pappalardi played bass on and produced West's debut solo album, Mountain (July 1969). Following its release, the two teamed up with drummer Norman Smart (soon replaced by Corky Laing) and keyboard player Steve Knight to form the Hard Rock band Mountain.

Eddie 'Fingers' Ojeda (born August 5, 1955 in New York) is one of the two guitarists of the American heavy metal band Twisted Sister. In the early 1970s he recorded a couple of singles with a band called SPX, with Alan Diaz, Charlie Mercado and Frank Lopez. He joined Twisted Sister in 1975. In 1989 he started the band Scarecrow.He also recorded a solo album named Axes To Axes in 2005 featuring Dee Snider, Ronnie James Dio and Rudy Sarzo among others. In a 2006 interview with rock & roll comic C.C. Banana, Eddie revealed if Twisted Sister ever retired that it would still be possible for the band to continue performing under their alternate name Bent Brother. Eddie, along with other popular rock guitarists in the mid-80's, performed in the Hear 'n Aid project, launched by Ronnie James Dio, which had a similar goal as both Band Aid and USA for Africa.

GREENY

The following instrument was built by the Gibson Custom Shop as a detailed replica of Peter Green's original Fleetwood Mac Burst. This Iconic burst was later owned by both Gary Moore and its current owner Kirk Hammett.

Gibson Custom Shop Collectors Choice No 1

Classic 59 Neck Profile carved to the original profile

Rosewood Fingerboard

Medium Jumbo Frets

BurstBucker Humbuckers

Sperzel Tuners as per original

Neck pickup reversed as per Peter Green preference

Ltd Run of 300 Guitars Worldwide

Original case, COA and Case Candy

History

Peter Green First bought his Les Paul from Selmer Music for the price of 60 pounds and was used on many classic Fleetwood Mac tracks including 'Oh Well', 'Black Magic Woman', 'Albatross' and 'Green Manalishi' in 1970 Green sold the guitar to up and coming guitarist Gary Moore who used the iconic burst across his career including his time with Thin Lizzy recording the iconic solo to 'Parisienne walkways' on it. Due to Financial Troubles Moore sold the Burst to UK collector Melvyn Franks who later sold the instrument onto Metallica Guitarist Kirk Hammett. In 2010 Gibson Honoured this iconic burst with the Collectors Choice No1 demonstrating its importance as one of the world's most famous bursts.

merged_product_data.model: Eric Clapton 'Artist Proof' 1964 Firebird I No 4 Played and owned by Eric
merged_product_data.description:
We are happy to offer the following instrument that was personally owned and used by one of the world's most legendary guitars that being Eric Clapton, details as follows

THE ERIC CLAPTON FIREBIRD I

History

In April 1968, during Cream's U.S. tour, Eric Clapton acquired a 1964 Gibson Firebird I, likely on April 13th in Philadelphia. This purchase is documented in Cream's tour ledger, which lists a 'musical equipment' expense of $905.50 on that date. The Firebird I featured a distinctive reverse body design and a single mini-humbucker pickup, offering a unique tone that set it apart from Clapton’s previous guitars. Before adopting the Firebird, Clapton was most famously associated with his Gibson SG, known as 'The Fool,' which was painted in a psychedelic design. The Firebird I represented a shift in both sound and style, providing a cutting, powerful tone that complemented Cream’s heavier blues-rock direction.

Clapton used the Firebird I extensively during Cream's final U.S. tour in 1968, as well as on their farewell performances at the Royal Albert Hall in London. The guitar was also played during the brief existence of Blind Faith, where Clapton experimented with a different musical approach. The Firebird’s raw tone and sustain made it a standout instrument for live performances, and it became a key part of Clapton’s signature sound in this period. Unlike the Gibson SG, which had a more rounded and warm tone, the Firebird I delivered a sharper attack, which suited Cream’s powerful improvisations on stage.

Reflecting on the guitar, Clapton later said,'I remember one night in particular with the Firebird. It was a Cream show in Philadelphia, and it was one of the greatest gigs I ever played.'His admiration for the Firebird I was evident in the way he integrated it into his performances, making it one of the defining instruments of his late-’60s era. The guitar's unique look and powerful sound contributed to some of the most memorable performances of his career, and it remains an iconic part of Clapton's history.

History

Wolfgang Palm is a German musician and inventor who was the founder and owner of Palm Products GmbH (PPG) and the inventor and creator of various pioneering technical designs for analog and digital synthesizers. He is widely acknowledged as the father of digital synthesis and as a trendsetter in the use of computer technology in the making of electronic music.

Palm's interest in synthesis technology began as a keyboardist in various local bands in his hometown of Hamburg, Germany. His namesake corporation began operating as early as 1975, manufacturing modular synthesizers in small numbers for electronica act Tangerine Dream and other musicians.

Palm is arguably most famous for the invention of wavetable synthesis, a concept which he developed in the late 1970s when he created his Minimoog-like synthesizer - the 1020 - featuring digitally controlled oscillators instead of the voltage-controlled oscillators that his 1002 synthesizer and all other analog synthesizers of that time were using. He also created the 360 Wavecomputer that would later become the renowned PPG Wave series. Palm's design was the impetus for the creation of the highly successful PPG Wave synthesizer, which was used by numerous bands throughout the 1980s and beyond.

THE PPG MODULAR SYSTEM

100, 200, and 300 Modules 2 Cabinets 1 Keyboard Each Module Hand Labelled by Wolfgang Palm

Cabinet one consists of :

3x 301 Voltage Controlled Oscillator 2x 104 Low Pass Filter 1x Oscillator with 3 Oscillators and Oscillator Driver 1x Wolfgang Palm Noise Generator 1x 217 Voltage Controlled Filter 3x 103 VCA 1x 309 Signal Mixer 4 x 109 Premix Interface 1x 111 CV interface/Reverb/Output Bass Treble/Power Supply

Cabinet Two Consists of:

3x107 Envelope Generator 3x 307 Dual Envelope Generator 1x 213 Step Sequencer 322 Duophonic Digital Keyboard

Notes: The keyboard comes with all the original German Manuals 230V Power supply and various patching cables

Users: PPG Synthesisers have been favored by a number of artists most famously the German Band Tangerine Dream / Klaus Schulze with such classic albums as Rubycon, Stratofear, Sorcerers

We are please to offer the following instrument which wasformerly owned by John Lennon of the Beatles. John Lennon’s Fender Duo Sonic • 1963 • Blonde Finish • Alder Body • Maple neck • Rosewood Fingerboard • 2x Single Coil pickups • Tortoiseshell Guard • Clay Dot Inlays • White Button Kluson Machineheads • Volume and Tone Controls • 3 Saddle Bridge For the full brochure please copy and paste the following link into your browser: online.flipbuilder.com/cmtr/fyvo/ History In 1974 Barrie Marshall was managing the musician Clive John (Clive Space) from the Welsh band, Man. On an upcoming trip to New York, Clive requested that Barrie purchase a short scale guitar that was similar to one John Lennon played. During his visit, Barrie met with a close personal friend, Mal Evans (John Lennon's PA / Beatles Technician) and discussed Clive's request. After further discussions he was then given one of John Lennon's personal instruments. This was not one of his legendary short scale Rickenbacker 325s that he’d used throughout his Beatles career, instead it was a Fender equivalent, that being his 1962 short scale Duo Sonic/Musicmaster model . On Barrie's return to the UK it was then given to Clive John who used it from 1974- 2011. Verification

  • Written verification from both Clive John and his widow Karin John confirming instruments history.
  • Photographic Verification of use from 1974 onwards.
  • Copy of Previous Auction Sale Listing in which instrument achieved £47,500 (2013).
  • Copy of Online Link to the John Lennon Instrument listing Site that confirms instrument was owned/used by John Lennon.

merged_product_data.model: Custom Acoustic ex George Harrison ' Thames Valley Special'
merged_product_data.description:
THEGEORGE HARRISON ZEMAITIS We are happy to offer one of the most exclusive and historically important of all Zemaitis guitars. Commissioned by George Harrison, this guitar was one of a set of 5 Instruments all of which carried unique and exclusive features which were never to repeated on any other Zemaitis guitars. Please find full details as

History confirmed by the Zemaitis Club

'George was a very generous person. In 1986, he decided to commission Tony to build a few guitars They were going to be acoustic guitars, but George wanted them to be even more special. After discussions with Tony, they decided to call the guitars “Thames Valley Specials”. The design would be strictly a limited edition of five acoustics. Tony asked Danny O’Brien to write out a certificate to accompany each of the guitars. It stated that “The sound hole decoration will never be repeated identically, except at the express wish of the certificate holders”.

Tony said George was very excited about the guitars. George wrote to Tony about the guitars.

“Tony, In a rush to get this to you – It’s a guess at a deposit on the Thames Valley Specials – and we’ll sort it out when I see you on the designs. At least you can go get the timber (if it is still available?). Will call mid week – till then all the best George. P.S. Deluxe Customs ??? Sounds good!! Lucky boys!”

You can feel George’s excitement in the letter. Tony kept the letter stuck on his workshop wall.

Specification - As follows

Zemaitis Thames Valley Special

1986 Commissioned by George Harrison Cedar Top Rosewood Back and Sides Heart Shaped Pearl Inlays Ebony Fingerboard Hand Engraved Truss Rod Cover Hand Tooled Fingerboard End Hand Signed by Tony Zemaitis

Note:The instrument offered was one of a set of 5 Instruments that was commissioned by George Harrison some of which were later gifted to several of his close personal friends and respected fellow musicians

Pictures Listed

Picture within the listing shows George Harrison, Alvin Lee and Joe Brown playing the Thames Valley Specials at Georges Harrisions's home at Henley on Thames. This shot was taken just after George had gifted the guitar to Joe and all five Thames Valley Specials can be seen

merged_product_data.model: Concerto 1000 Electric Piano owned and used by Rick Wakeman of YES
merged_product_data.description: We are happy to offer the following items from the personal private collection of iconic keyboardist and synth collector Rick Wakeman. Rick career has spanned over 50 years including his time with The Strawbs and YES through to his session work with David Bowie, Black Sabbath and countless others. Alongside this, Rick's own solo career has pushed the boundaries of possibilities in terms of his use of the synthesiser including his albums Journey to the Centre of the Earth and the Six wives of Henry VIII. Rick is now pleased to be offering his fans the chance to owns some of the pieces which have sculpted his sound across his extensive career. Please find details of these pieces as below: Valdesta Concerto 1000 Electric Piano The Valdesta Concerto 1000 has the elegance of a baby grand piano with the benefits of a feature-packed ensemble digital piano. It has 500 different professional quality sounds, programmable effects, and a 3.5 disk drive. It has an all-wood hand polished baby grand cabinet with brass plated pedals, dual-prop lifting piano lid, roll top key cover, one-piece brass hinge, and split brass caster wheels. Used by Rick on YESACOUSTIC Each item will come with written verification direct from Rick Wakeman to confirm his ownership and use of the items. Pricing All items have been in storage many since the 1970s and will require servicing by the purchaser. This costing is reflected in the pricing of each item.

We are pleased to offer the following limited edition amplifier built to honour the 50th anniversary of the iconic Texas blues band ZZ TOP

ZZ Top 50th Anniversary Super Fifity Nine M80 Head and Cab

Combining the Tone and Gain Stages of the MKI and MKII into one Footswitchable and Flexible Package

We've put the Super Fifty-Nine MK I and MK II models into one versatile tone machine. This 45 watt, EL-34 driven 80th anniversary model combines the low to medium gain tones of the MKII with the extra gain stage of the MK I. Access it all via front switch or footswitch. Comes with a tube buffered effects loop, and the same palette of tone controls as the other models. We've created a clear signal path of pure tonal bliss.

The M80 combines the gain flavors of the MKI & MKII in one convenient package. No vibrato is included on this model and the result is raw, open, and in your face. Choose between high and low gain modes for ultimate flexibility in your playing style.

Backlit logo

BRITISH ICON THE WHO are one of the world most iconic of all Rock 'n' Roll Bands, their style inspired and influenced a new generation in terms of both fashion, music and cultural identity. Selling over 100 Million records worldwide, THE WHO are within a select number of musical artists define the term 'ICONIC' The Collection The following items were purchased directly from THE WHO’s Personal Hire company “ ML EXECUTIVE “ which was formed in 1977 - 1978 , please see exert from the web site [Shepperton] serves as a home for the equipment hire company that the Who set up for their road crew, ML Executives. The Who had built up the biggest and finest collection of sound equipment of any band in the world, but were touring less and less. This expensive equipment, plus their top road crew were very much in demand by other bands, so they set up ML Executives to hire out the equipment when they weren’t using it. BPC WEM PEP BOX

Celebrating 50 years since its creation, the British Pedal company WEM PEPBOX is a detailed replica of the original unit designed by Pepe Rush for WEM around 1965. This pedal was most famously used by John Lennon at Abbey Road studios during the Revolver Session and can be seen on many photographs from the period. The pedal features 2 Germanium ACY41 Transistors as per the original unit and is housed in a metal enclosure with engraved logo and control panels. The front panel features effect which acts as the gain and then a Level control for the overall volume.

merged_product_data.model: Prototype Precision Bass ex Dusty Hill ZZ TOP
merged_product_data.description:
*** ALL EU PURCHASES ARE DELIVERED WITH TAXES AND DUTIES PAID ***

ZZ Top call themselves 'that little ol' band from Texas,' a deceptively clever designation that explains everything about the trio while underselling their deep idiosyncrasies. At their core, the trio of Billy Gibbons, Frank Beard, and Dusty Hill were a down-and-dirty blues band from Houston, cranking out greasy rockers and slyly sleazy boogies about 'Tush,' a 'Pearl Necklace,' and 'Legs.' Despite their deep roots in American rock & roll and blues, ZZ Top were the furthest thing from purists. During their hot streak -- which ran all the way from the mid-'70s through the mid-'80s –- there wasn't a fad they didn't exploit, twisting new wave, synthesized dance-rock, and music videos for their own purposes. Throughout it all, they wrapped all their hooks and riffs up in a smile disguised by bushy beards and flashy showmanship that not only earned the group a massive audience, but endured well into the 21st century, when they were surrounded by disciples and acolytes, proof that they were a beloved American musical institution.

Fender Dusty Hill Custom Prototype Precision Bass Black 50s P Bass Style Reverse Headstock Custom Shop Produced Hand Signed by Dusty Hill History - The above instrument is a Prototype produced within the Fender Custom Shop and can be seen in both live and video performances COA - Instrument comes full detailed and signed verification to confirm use / ownership Note - ZZ Top are one of he most recognised and distinct of all Rock N Roll bands and are renowned for there use of unique and distinct instruments

THE GARY MOORE 1963 FENDER STRATOCASTER We are happy to offer the following that was owned/used by one of the world's most respected and influential of all artists, that is Gary Moore. This specific instrument is one of his most iconic instrument as it was synonymous to both his look and tone Gary Moore's playing style was unique, working with many artists including Eric Clapton, Thin Lizzy, BB King, Joe Walsh and many more. He is most remembered for the iconic track Parisienne walkways with its memorable sustained melody that helped him to be known as one of the worlds finest guitarists of all time Fender Stratocaster 1963 ( Pre Cbs) Natural Rosewood Neck S / No L21725 Custom Pickup Options based GMs specification Hardshell Case History The instrument was one of a select number of instruments that was offered for sale in 2015 by Bonhams auctioneers and was then purchased for a private collection , please see original 2016 auction description THE GARY MOORE COLLECTION Gary Moore: A Fender Stratocaster guitar, 1963, neckplate stamped L21725, body clear-lacquered natural finish, three Kinman AVN pickups, three-ply laminated scratchplate, three volume/tone knobs and five-way selector, re-fretted rosewood fingerboard with dot markers, in rectangular, plush-lined Fender tweed case with various components, guitar 38 1/2in (98cm) long FOOTNOTES This was a gift to Gary from the late Claude Nobs, founder of the Montreux Jazz Festival, during a performance there in 1998. The guitar required extensive work ( By Gary Moore ) to return it to a playable condition, including complete re-fret, new tremolo block, replacement tuners, re-wiring and a set of Kinman noiseless pickups. With the guitar is an alternative, complete additional hardware/electronics setup mounted on a separate scratchplate, with Stratocaster single coil pickups by Seymour Duncan. They were made for Gary with a number of options, one of which is a reverse-wound single coil, providing an additional set of tones when used in certain pickup combinations. Seen on the live footage of the TV broadcast from the Fledah in Finsbury Park, London in 2001 and the 'Blues For Jimi' DVD, filmed in London in late 2007. Featured in the 'Guitarist' magazine, Issue 403, February 2016, Gary Moore Commemorative Edition and demonstrated on Youtube. Verification The instrument comes with detailed verification as follows Video / Film Footage Of Artist Official Verification from Artist management confirming use / ownership Copy Of Original Bonhams Catalogue featuring the said instrument Copy of Guitarist Magazine in which the guitar was featured Video Links - Please see various video links - Enjoy the viewing of one of the worlds Greats : )) FINSBURY PARK ( See 63 ST From 4 .15) BLUES FOR JIMI ( See 63 ST From 21.28 Mins ) FINSBURY PARK Comments The above is one of the most important and recognised of all gary moore instruments that carries full written and photographic verification , interest from both collectors , investors , players will high based on rarity and importance to said artist

CREAMS DELUXE FENDER GUITAR AMPLIFIER We are happy to offer the following amplifier which was used by one of the most iconic of all bands that is ' Cream' that consisted of Eric Clapton ( Guitar ) , Jack Bruce ( Bass ) , Ginger Baker ( Drums ) History Cream to many are regarded as the worlds first super group. Made of up Ginger Baker, Eric Clapton and Jack Bruce they were both iconic and inspirational to many artists including Led Zeppelin, Deep Purple, Black Sabbath . Their unique fusion of jazz, blues , rock and psychedelia can be heard on classic hits such as Crossroads, Strange Brew, Born Under a Bad Sign White Room Specification Fender Deluxe Reverb Guitar Amplifier

  • 1966
  • Black Face
  • 1x12 Speaker Configuration
  • 20 Watts
  • Internally / Externally Original

Verification The amplifier comes with full written and photographic verification as follows Letter from Malcolm Bruce ( Son) to confirm the Fender Deluxe Reverb Guitar amplifier was used within his fathers time with Cream , i.e. Eric Clapton Guitar , Ginger Baker Drums , Jack Bruce Bass Note During Eric Claptons time with Cream he can be seen usingseveral Fender Black Face Guitar amplifiers for both live and studio purposes To Summarise The above has been released for general sale from the family one of Creams founding members, Mr Jack Bruce and is among a select number of important and historical musical artifacts that defined a musical genre.

BPC MKI.5 Tone Bender.

Often known as the mythical fuzz due to the very few original examples which exist, the MKI.5 Tone Bender was produced in 1966 and was the first tone bender that featured the iconic Grey Hammerite Aluminium Casing. The MKI.5 featured a different circuit than the earlier production MK I which consisted of a 2x OC75 transistor circuit At the time of production one of these rare fuzzes managed to find its way into Abbey Road Studios and was pictured being used by George Harrison of The Beatles.

BPC MKI.5 Tone Bender.

  • Aluminum cast casing
  • Level and Attack controls
  • 2x OC75 Transistors
  • As used by the Beatles
  • Limited production
  • Certificate of authenticity

BPC Professional MKII Tone Bender

The BPC MKII Tone Bender OC81D is a detailed replica of the 1966 PROFESSIONAL MK II Tone Bender pedals created by Gary Hurst. The circuit unlike the MK 1.5 had a 3 Transistor circuit which, based on production/supply comprised of either OC75’s or OC81D transistors. This OC81D Loaded MK II can be heard on many Jimmy/Led Zeppelin Tracks such as ‘Whole lotta love’. This was the pedal seen being used by Jimmy on the recent ‘It Might get loud ‘ documentary.

BPC Professional MKII Tone Bender OC81D.

  • Aluminum cast casing
  • Level and Attack controls

  • Limited production

Dallas Rangemaster Varitone Treble Booster

The New Dallas Rangemaster Varitone takes the traditional treble booster to a new level. Introducing a new linear gain circuit and modified tone network this new treble booster offers the user a stepped variable frequency selector allowing the user to dial in the perfect sweet spot both in terms of gain and tonal performance. The new Dallas Rangemaster Varitone features a specially produced OC75 Transistor, hand selected for its optimum performance over the tonal spectrum.

merged_product_data.model: Ltd Edition MKI Wooden Case Tone Bender
merged_product_data.description:
Description

BPC MKI Wooden Case Prototype Tone Bender

The UK fuzz box phenomenon began in 1965 when electronics engineer Gary Stewart Hurst designed an effects pedal called a Tone Bender. The first production version of the Tone Bender is referred to as the Tone Bender MKI. The MKI featured a three transistor circuit that was based upon the Gibson built Maestro Fuzz-tone. This circuit was modified by Hurst to produce more sustain than its American counter part. The story goes that guitar legend Vic Flick, the man responsible for the James Bond Theme, brought a Fuzz-tone (FZ-1) to Hurst and requested the sustain to be increased. The Tone Bender was one the first ever British made Fuzz box available to the public and sold for 14 guineas. THE BIRTH OF BRITISH FUZZ WAS BORN!

Casing

The original “PROTOTYPE” units were housed in a primitive wooden box case and were distributed to session players on the London scene including Jeff Beck. Due to Beck’s heavy use of the pedal he smashed the unit with his heavy foot stomping movements while playing on stage. As word got out about Gary Hurst new design he changed the construction material to steel in order to live up to the rigours of stage use. Comments If Fuzz is your thing then the above will be of interest from both players and collectors a like that creates both the look styling and tone of Britains most famous and iconic of all fuzz effects

BPC MKITone Bender

  • 2x 2G381 + 1x OC75
  • Correct Period Aluminium Knobs
  • Top Input Jack
  • Rear Output Jack
  • Manual On/Off Switch
  • Hand Stained Finish
  • 10 Models Produced worldwide
  • Internally signed and Numbered by Builder ( 1 – 10 )
  • Ltd Edition Certificate

BPC MKI Tone Bender

The BPC MKI Tone Bender is a detailed replica of the original 1965 Metal Case Tone Bender pedal created by Gary Hurst in London, England. The BPC MKI features the same transistor specification as the original so includes 1x OC75 + 2x 2G381 this configuaration has a unique tone which cannot be replicated by the often offered 3xOC75 version. It was this version which found its way into the hands of artists such as Jeff Beck, Pete Townsend and Mick Ronson and can be heard on many classic tracks such as ‘Hang onto yourself’ and ‘Moonage Daydream’.

BPC MKI Tone Bender

  • Folded metal casing
  • Level and Attack controls
  • 1x OC75 + 2x 2G381
  • Limited production
  • As used by Jeff Beck, Mick Ronson and Pete Townshend
  • Certificate of authenticity
